ABSTRACT
This project presents a comprehensive and scalable system for predictive mental health monitoring by leveraging machine learning, natural language processing, cloud deployment, and mobile application integration. The system is designed to analyze user-generated data, particularly text and behavioral patterns, to identify the most dominant mental health disorder affecting an individual. With the increasing use of digital platforms where users frequently express emotions, thoughts, and experiences, such data serves as a valuable source for early detection of psychological conditions.
The work begins with the collection of multiple datasets representing various mental health conditions such as depression, anxiety, stress, bipolar disorder and suicidal tendencies. These datasets include both structured and unstructured formats, enabling the system to capture a wide range of indicators. Extensive preprocessing techniques are applied, including data cleaning, normalization, and transformation, along with Natural Language Processing methods such as tokenization, stop-word removal, lemmatization, and TF-IDF vectorization. These steps ensure that the data is converted into meaningful features suitable for machine learning models.
Multiple machine learning algorithms are implemented, including Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost, Support Vector Machine, and Neural Networks. Each model is trained and evaluated using standard performance metrics such as accuracy, precision, recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC. Comparative analysis is conducted to identify the best-performing model, ensuring both accuracy and efficiency. The selected models demonstrate high predictive performance, achieving accuracy levels exceeding 90% across different datasets.
A key contribution of this system is the transformation of trained models from PKL format into ONNX format. This conversion enables platform independence, faster inference, and reduced dependency on specific programming environments. The ONNX models are then deployed on the Hugging Face platform, which provides scalable cloud infrastructure and API-based access to the models. This deployment allows real-time interaction between the backend system and external applications.
To enhance usability, a mobile application is developed using Android Studio. The application serves as the user interface, allowing individuals to input their data and receive predictions in real time. The app communicates with the deployed API by sending user input and receiving prediction results, which indicate the most affected mental health disorder. This seamless integration of backend intelligence and frontend accessibility ensures that the system is practical and user-friendly.
The overall system follows a structured workflow that includes data collection, preprocessing, model training, evaluation, conversion, deployment, and application integration. This step-by-step approach ensures scalability, modularity, and maintainability. The system is capable of delivering fast and accurate predictions while maintaining efficiency through optimized deployment strategies.
The results demonstrate that ensemble models such as XGBoost and CatBoost provide superior performance due to their ability to capture complex patterns in data. The use of ONNX significantly improves inference speed, while cloud deployment ensures high availability and scalability. The Android application successfully provides real-time predictions, making the system accessible to end users.
This project highlights the potential of artificial intelligence in supporting mental health monitoring and early detection. While the system is not intended to replace professional diagnosis, it serves as a powerful tool for awareness and preliminary assessment. The modular design allows future enhancements such as integration with real-time social media data, advanced deep learning models, personalized recommendations, and improved visualization dashboards.
In conclusion, the project successfully demonstrates the transformation of machine learning models into a fully deployed, real-time application. It bridges the gap between research and practical implementation, providing a scalable, efficient, and user-friendly solution for predictive mental health monitoring.






