CHAPTER 1 – INTRODUCTION
1.1 Problem Introduction
In recent years, the rapid growth of social media platforms has transformed the way individuals express their thoughts, emotions, and daily experiences. Platforms such as Reddit, Twitter, Instagram, and Facebook have become digital environments where users openly share their mental states, personal struggles, and behavioural patterns. This continuous stream of user-generated content provides a valuable data source for analyzing psychological conditions using computational methods.
Mental health disorders such as depression, anxiety, stress, bipolar disorder and suicidal ideation are increasing at a significant rate globally. Traditional methods of diagnosis rely on clinical observations and self-reporting, which often fail to capture real-time emotional changes or early warning signals. Therefore, there is a strong need for an automated system that can continuously monitor and analyze behavioral and textual patterns to detect mental health risks at an early stage.
The developed system addresses this problem by leveraging machine learning and natural language processing techniques to analyze social media-like data and predict the most dominant mental health disorder affecting a user. The system evolves from a data-driven model pipeline into a fully functional application capable of delivering real-time predictions.
1.2 Motivation
The motivation behind this work arises from the increasing digital presence of individuals and the rich psychological signals embedded in their online activities. People often express emotions such as sadness, stress, loneliness, or anxiety through posts, comments, and interactions. These expressions, when analyzed correctly, can provide meaningful insights into their mental health condition.
Initially, the work focused on building a strong machine learning pipeline capable of handling multiple datasets and predicting different disorders with high accuracy. However, having a trained model alone is not sufficient for real-world impact. There was a need to transform this model into a usable system that could interact with users and provide real-time insights.
This led to the motivation for extending the work into a complete application by integrating model deployment, API communication, and mobile application development. The goal was to create an end-to-end intelligent system that bridges the gap between machine learning models and real-world usability.
1.3 Project Objectives
The primary objectives of this work are structured to reflect the transition from model development to full system deployment:
• To develop a robust machine learning pipeline capable of processing textual and structured data for predicting multiple mental health disorders.
• To train and evaluate multiple models such as Logistic Regression, Random Forest, Gradient Boosting, XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost, and Neural Networks using appropriate evaluation metrics.
• To convert trained machine learning models from PKL format to ONNX format to ensure platform independence, faster inference, and better deployment compatibility.
• To deploy the ONNX models on a cloud platform (Hugging Face) and expose them through APIs for real-time access.
• To design and develop an Android application using Android Studio that interacts with the deployed API and displays prediction results to the user.
• To create a complete workflow where the mobile application sends user data to the API and receives predictions indicating the most affected mental health disorder.
• To build a scalable and modular system that can be extended with additional features such as real-time monitoring, advanced models, and personalized recommendations.
1.4 Scope of the Project
The scope of this work covers the complete lifecycle of a machine learning-based application, starting from data processing to real-time deployment and user interaction.
In the initial phase, the work focuses on dataset handling, preprocessing, feature engineering, and training multiple machine learning models for different mental health conditions. This includes handling both structured and textual data using NLP techniques and statistical methods.
In the extended phase, the scope expands to include model conversion, deployment, and application integration. The trained models are converted into ONNX format to ensure compatibility with different platforms. These models are then deployed on Hugging Face, where they are exposed as APIs.
The Android application serves as the front-end interface, allowing users to interact with the system. The app sends requests to the API, receives predictions, and displays the disorder that most significantly affects the user.
The system is designed to be scalable and adaptable, allowing future enhancements such as integration with live social media data, real-time monitoring, and advanced deep learning techniques.
1.5 Related Previous Work (Brief)
Previous research in mental health prediction has primarily focused on analyzing social media data using machine learning and natural language processing techniques. Studies have shown that linguistic patterns, sentiment analysis, and behavioral features can be effectively used to detect conditions such as depression and anxiety.
Many existing systems focus on single-condition prediction, such as detecting depression from Twitter data or identifying suicidal ideation from text posts. These systems often use models like Support Vector Machines, Logistic Regression, or deep learning approaches such as LSTM and BERT.
In contrast, this work extends beyond traditional approaches by integrating multiple disorder predictions into a unified system and further transforming the model into a deployable application. The key advancement lies in the transition from offline model development to a real-time, API-driven mobile application.
Additionally, the use of ONNX for model conversion and Hugging Face for deployment introduces a modern, scalable approach to machine learning system design. The integration with an Android application further enhances accessibility and usability, making the system practical for real-world implementation.
This structured progression from model development to deployment and application integration distinguishes the work and highlights its contribution to the field of predictive mental health monitoring.

 
